<QuickQuiz
  question="When interest rates rise, what typically happens to existing bond prices?"
  options={[
    { text: "Bond prices rise too", correct: false },
    { text: "Bond prices fall", correct: true },
    { text: "Bond prices are unaffected", correct: false },
    { text: "Bond prices rise initially then fall", correct: false }
  ]}
  explanation="Bonds and interest rates have an inverse relationship. When rates rise, newly issued bonds pay more interest, making existing bonds (with lower rates) less attractive — so their market price falls. When rates fall, existing bonds with higher rates become more valuable and their prices rise. This is why long-term bonds are more sensitive to rate changes than short-term bonds."
/>
